# Don't leave temp files in the repo

Never leave build logs, scratch output, or throwaway files sitting in the
working tree — even if `.gitignore` would hide them (e.g. `*.log`). They clutter
the repo and confuse the next agent.

## Build output

The Shell tool already captures full command output to a terminal file, so you
almost never need to redirect a build to a file. Do NOT do this:

```powershell
# BAD - dumps a 700 KB log into the repo root that lingers forever
& $msbuild d:\dev\vm\VisualMusic.sln /p:Platform=x64 > build_fix.log 2>&1
```

Just run the build and read the captured output. If output is huge, it's already
written to the terminal file for you to read in full.

## When you genuinely need a scratch file

- Write it under the system temp dir, not the repo: `$env:TEMP` (PowerShell) or
  `/tmp` — e.g. `"$env:TEMP\vm_build.log"`.
- If a temp file must live in the repo (e.g. a plan you're iterating on), delete
  it before you finish the task.

## Before ending a task

Check for stray files you created and remove them:

```powershell
git -C d:\dev\vm status --ignored --porcelain | Select-String "build.*\.log|scratch|\.tmp"
```

Leave the working tree exactly as clean as you found it.
